06933nam a22009375i 9783110529098DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20172018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105290987 a10.1515/97831105290982doi  a(DE-B1597)474812  a(OCoLC)1020033307  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aGV603b.B49 2018 7aHIS0370802bisacsh04a796.09422300aBeyond Boycotts :bSport during the Cold War in Europe /ced. by Philippe Vonnard, Nicola Sbetti, Grégory Quin. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2017] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (VIII, 234 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRethinking the Cold War ,x2567-5311 ;v100tFrontmatter -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tFirst Part. Creating relations between European states. Sport as tool of diplomacy -- tPlaying at the border of the Cold War -- tAn Even Colder War? -- tAthletes of Diplomacy -- tSecond part. A European space of exchanges. Crossing the Iron Curtain with sport -- tThe emergence of Europe-wide collaboration and competition -- tBuilding bridges between separated Europeans -- tCooperation and conflict -- tThird Part. Globalizing sport. Europe as a site of international sporting diplomacy -- t"Shooting Hoops with Foreign Teams" -- tThe Ghana Young Pioneers -- t"The Russian deadpan expert" vs "America's white hope" -- tA forgotten "ping-pong diplomacy"? -- tAfterword -- tBibliography -- tContributors (by alphabetical order) -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aSport during Cold War has recently begun to be studied in more depth. Some scholars have edited a book about the US and Soviet sport diplomacy and show ow the government of these two countries have used sport during this period, notably as a tool of "soft power" during the Olympic games. Our goal is to continue in this direction and to focus more on the sport field as a place of exchanges during the Cold War. Regarding this point, our aim is to show that there were events "beyond boycotts"many and that unknown connections existed inside sport. Morevoer, many actors were involved in these exchanges. Thus, it is important not only to focus on the action of States, but also on private actors (international sporting bodies and journalists), considering that they acted around sport (an "apolitic" field) as it was tool to maintain links between the two blocs. Our project offers a good opportunity for young scholars to present original research based on new materials (notably the use of institutional or personals archives). Morevoer, it is also a step forward with a view to conduct research within a global history paradigm, one that is still underused in sport academic fields.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aCold WarxPolitical aspectszEurope. 0aCold WarxSocial aspectszEurope. 0aSportsxPolitical aspectszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aSportszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 4aEuropa. 4aKalter Krieg. 4aSport. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 21st Century.2bisacsh  aSport history, Cold War, Diplomacy, Entanglements.1 aDoppler-Speranza, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDufraisse, Sylvain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarston, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaha, Souvik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNicolas, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb